# ContextFit changes how agents remember {#opening}

::scene id=intro role=hook
::layout mode=hero emphasis=title
::motion sequence=claim-then-proof pace=deliberate

:::claim id=contextfit-thesis source=whitepaper#token-native
Agents do not need bigger context windows as much as they need better memory retrieval.
::

:::beat id=old-way role=problem reveal=1 source=whitepaper#vector-loss
Most retrieval systems translate memory into vector space and lose source-level structure.
::

:::beat id=new-way role=reframe reveal=2 source=whitepaper#token-native
ContextFit stays token-native, making memory indexable, attributable, and agent-friendly.
::

:::takeaway id=opening-takeaway
The real product is not a slide; it is a structured argument graph.
::

:::speaker-notes
Open by contrasting context stuffing with retrieval quality.
::

## Why md, tmd, and smd belong together {#format-triad}

::scene id=format-triad role=framework
::layout mode=grid
::motion sequence=left-to-right pace=normal

:::beat id=md-format role=example reveal=1
`.md` captures narrative knowledge: human-readable explanation.
::

:::beat id=tmd-format role=example reveal=2
`.tmd` captures structured rows: queryable, appendable, and formula-friendly.
::

:::beat id=smd-format role=example reveal=3
`.smd` captures sequenced story: indexable beats plus presentation direction.
::

:::takeaway id=format-triad-takeaway
ContextFit should treat communication artifacts as first-class memory objects.
::
